bug.short_desc: Authorization for Sessions with BIRT runtime

long_desc.thetext: In order to grant privacy and access control to data in bigger databases, it is necessary to have user authentication (username & password) in BIRT in order to perform somehow authorization for viewing specific data. Today i solve this by asking the user for username & password as parameters for a report. It would be more convenient to have a one time authentication e.g. against an L-DAP-Server within Tomcat and have the username and password as hidden parameters available from the Tomcat session without having to program a JNDI-source to acquire this data.

One possible solution is to use the appContext object on BIRT engine and ODA APIs to pass the username and passwd from your App's tomcat session down to the place where you need to use it for data access.
please let us know more about your app's data and control flow if the appContext object doesn't work for you.
DTE might provide a machanism or system to accept the user defined authorization config and control the data access. Assign to DTE team to investigate this.

(In reply to comment #2) > DTE might provide a machanism or system to accept the user defined > authorization config and control the data access. Assign to DTE team to > investigate this.
AppContext is such a mechanism.

Authentication logic against LDAP or other services is highly application-specific and is somewhat difficult to generalize and be supported out-of-the-box by BIRT. The authentication code will have to be provided by the application, then plugged into BIRT through any of these available means:
(1) Use Scripting or Property Binding feature of BIRT to override data source connection properties (username/password etc.) The Scripts or Binding expressions can refer to external Java objects which does the authentication and provides the actual property value to use at runtime.
(2) An existing extension point propertyProvider of the DTP org.eclipse.datatools.connectivity.oda.consumer plugin (which is used by BIRT) provides for a way for connection properties to be overwritten at runtime. You will need to implement this extension-point in a plugin available to BIRT. This is slightly more complicated than (1) but has the advantage that you won't need to do this in each individual report design.
Please review these approaches and let us know if they address your use case, and if not, supply more information about your requirements and any suggested solutions.
please reopen the bug if the comments provided does not address your usage.

I made a initial implementation for this feature. Feel free to make any suggestions.
It contributes 3 commands:
- Open Task -> Ctrl+Shift+F11. - Activate Task -> Ctrl+Shift+F12. - Deactivate All Tasks -> Ctrl+Shift+F9.

They support filtering on tasks and query hits, and persist the position/size across open/close sessions.
They also use the task activation history to make proposals on filtering, like "Open Type" (filtered tasks who are in history have higher priority than the others; the others came up after the history proposals in alphabetical order).

bug.short_desc: Can not paste a image into RTE

long_desc.thetext:
OS: Windows XP with SP2 Language: English Build: epf-composer-1.0-M4-N20060727-1715-win32
Description: Cannot paste an image from clipboard to the unexpanded or expanded rich text field.
Works for me in 2006033102

In epf-composer-1.0-M4-N20060801-1350-win32, I put a bmp image in the clipboard, and it can be pasted into Word correctly. Using the context menu or the tool bar to paste this image, a dirty flag is raised, a place holder is put in the RTE, and some html source is generated, but image could not be rendered.

This was broken for EPF when SWT changed their implementation of the HTMLTransfer class. A temporary workaround is to use Firefox as your source browser, instead of IE.
When putting HTML info on the clipboard, Internet Explorer keeps relative paths in all href's and src's. There is also a SourceURL: field in the HTML metadata on the clipboard that provides the base URL that the paths are relative to. The old implementation of SWT gave us all of this metadata, so that we could resolve the paths and find the files in order to copy them into the library. The new SWT is not giving us the metadata, and so the files can't be located.
Firefox avoids this whole issue by providing full paths in href's and src's when putting them on the clipboard.

Fixed by implementing a new Win2HTMLTransfer class to retrieve the HTML source URL from the Windows clipboard. This class is win32 specific and is packaged in a new plug-in named "org.eclipse.epf.common.win32.win32.x86".

bug.short_desc: Incremental compiler doesn't handle exception declaration correctly

long_desc.thetext: Thanks for the simple testcase. Reproduced with latest AJDT. Any change causing an incremental build seems to show the problem.

between the first and second compiles we flush/clear the 'expendablemap' of types in the type map. We shouldn't do that. expendablemap is a weakhashmap and as soon as noone is using the values in the map in some way, they are free for GC. flushing/clearing the expendable map by forces mean removing something that someone may still be using. In this case the first compilation resolved IOException and got a referencetype back. When the map is flushed, we re-resolve IOException on the second compile and get a different referencetype - these are not == and so we fail. We do not use 'equals()' comparisons, because that's a whole world of pain.
Basically, expendableMap is a 'workingset' of types currently in use, it should be free to manage its own contents as a weakhashmap - anyone forcably managing the contents can cause this kind of problem.
Committed the testcase (thanks for the clear test program) and fix.
fix available in AJ dev builds.

bug.short_desc: [KeyBindings] Key bindings do not play well with dynamic action enablement

long_desc.thetext:

It uses selectionChanged() to dynamically enable/disable the action. It is disabled for any file with a name that starts with "disabled". The action in question is bound to a command responding to Alt+Shift+E.
Steps to recreate bug:
1) Create two files named enabled.txt and disabled.txt
2) Select enabled.txt and type Alt+Shift+E. Dialog pops up (as it should).
3) Select disabled.txt and type Alt+Shift+E. Dialog pops up. It should not as TestAction.selectionChanged() has disabled the action.
4) Select enabled.txt and type Alt+Shift+E. Dialog does not pop up (but it should). Alt+Shift+E is now effectively dead.
(and the KEYS trace will always report:
KEYS >>> WorkbenchKeyboard.press(potentialKeyStrokes = [ALT+SHIFT+E]) KEYS >>> WorkbenchKeyboard.executeCommand(commandId = 'gov.wicourts.eclipsebug1.testAction', parameters = {}) KEYS >>> not enabled
)
The problem appears to be that the action enabled state is only checked prior to calling IActionDelegate.selectionChanged() instead of after calling it.
The first time selectionChanged() disables the action, it will be run anyway since the action was enabled going in. However, thereafter, the action will remain disabled forever since selectionChanged() is never called again.
It looks like this might be related to bug 151612 and/or bug 140345.

I think this is related to the keybinding-handler-IAction not being tied to the workbench window IAction.
PW

bug.short_desc: Validate additional.bundles against trailing whitespace after the continuation character

long_desc.thetext:
I just noticed that sometimes the color highlighting for the additional.bundles property values was not always working. On investigation it seems that when using the '\' continuation character any trailing whitespace immediately following the continuation character caused syntax highlighting to stop. The side effects of this might be benign, but I'm not sure.
I tried adding some whitespace immediately after the continuation character for the bin.includes property and it results in the following, rather cryptic, error in the Problems view:
: directory entries must end with '/' ("/")
While this error means little to me (as it results to trailing whitespace), I'm grateful for it since it tipped me off that something was adrift. The syntax highlighting also stopped after the additional whitespace in this case.
So, at a minimum, I'd like to see a warning if whitespace is trailing a continuation character, but better still, how about just automatically trimming any trialing whitespace?
I would even go as far as saying that any trailing whitespace at the END of any property value should always be trimmed by the editor, since to make whitespace significant you only need to add quotes. But maybe that's another bug report altogether. ;-)

Automatically modifying whitespace in a user's file could cause users headaches. I know Wassim has been a big proponent of not trying to do things wtihout the user's knowledge. Though we don't always agree, if we trimmed whitespaces we are actually changing the way the file is read. If we do that automatically, the user's application might work differently if they open the file, make it dirty (space + backspace), and save the file.
As far as the warning, I could see that as a solution. Do you see this as something we might be able to piggy back on an existing PDE compiler tag? Is this something that should be configurable or just always marked as a warning?

You've convinced me that changing the file for the user automatically is probably a bad idea.
But warning the user about trialing whitespace should be something that the PDE always does, particular with regard to the additional.bundles property. I'm not sure that this is appropriate for all properties, but rather on a case by case basis.
Trailing whitespace already causes the color highlighting to go adrift, which seems to me to be a good starting point. In other words, if the color highlighting is adrift then I would always expect a warning to bring the issue to my attention.
Not sure about everyone else but I feel a quick fix coming on...

all right. I'm back from vacation. let me weigh in :)
As Simon observed, the syntax highlighting does go adrift when there is a trailing space. A warning would be good here as well. No need for a new flag. All build.properties problems are lumped under one flag.
As for a quickfix, it may not be worth it, since it requires more clicks to view/execute the quickfix than to delete the trailing space manually :)

I have a small hesitation about using the general build.properties tag. The whitespace is a guideline to prevent mistakes. The user might put the extra space/s there on purpose. If the user set the severity of build.properties to error, then we are flagging and error on something that might not be wrong.
We can tell the user if this happens and they want to get ride of it, to set the general severity of build.properties markers to warning/ignore. I was trying to think of the behavior our users would be looking for as far as severity/ignoring them.
As far as the quickfix, I would agree with Wassim that this does not warrant one.

> The user might put the extra space/s there on purpose.
Question: Can you think of a scenario in which a developer would purposely add trailing whitespace to a property value?
I have never purposely done this, so to me it is always a mistake.

-> e.g. choice -> sequence -> element multiplicity = <element max occurs> * <sequence max occurs> * <choice max occurs>
-> Only add a new proposal for a given element if it has not exceeded the multiplicity
-> Note: This is a simple calculation that does not address all complex XML Schema multiplity rules. For instance, multiple layers of choices and sequences compositors coupled with varying siblings elements require a regex processor For the PDE space this is not required as extension point schemas are always very simple
